trip_comments: Migration watch only at lighthouse area. Very busy morning with not only a big movement of YRWA's but also some interesting birds especially prior and during start of brisk wind and rain moving in. Partly to mostly cloudy to start with calm winds becoming light from south. Lull in action had me ready to complete a bit after 10 but quick stop in and visit by a WEKI prompted additional watch time. At about 11, wind picked up to 15+ and rain started and birds like YRWA's actually started to land rather than fly on. Temps starting in upper 40's to start and 53 at completion.

trip_comments: 70% cloud cover, calm to 8-12 mph wind at beach, 59*F at start; Tom Edell and Curtis Marantz. We parked at the north end of Creek Road, walked into the dry creek bed of Arroyo Grande Creek, and worked our way down creek. When we reached the horse trail crossing, when continued down creek along the berm on the southern side of the creek. After taking a short detour on a side trail to look at the last pines and peek at the ponded area west of the private house, we continued west along the horse trail to the dunes and then found a route through the dunes to an overlook of the creek mouth lagoon.  The lagoon was restricted to a small portion of the normally flooded area with most of it to the southern end of the historic lagoon. We then headed north through the dunes to the dry creek bed and after crossing the creek walked east along the berm on the north side of the creek bed to the horse trail, crossed the dry creek bed again, and continued east along the south berm to where we parked the cars. The total distance covered was 2.05 miles, with only the horse crossing covered twice.  The walk along the southern berm back to the cars paralleled the initial walk in the creek bed but allowed us to scan the horse facility's fields and was therefore included in the total mileage.  Without adding that mileage, the distance traveled would have been 1.6 miles. Submitted from eBird Android 1.3-beta6

trip_comments: 25 % cloud cover, 4-7 mph NW wind,  55*F; Tom Edell and Maggie Smith participating in the Santa Maria/Guadalupe CBC. We parked at Jack O'Connell park and walked to the waste water plant access road and then cut left along a dirt road behind some farm buildings and continued on along the road separating the agricultural fields from the pasture with cows.  The pasture was partially flooded and the channel along the fence was partially filled with water. We scoped the pasture and pond at the north side of the field as we walked west along the road. Eventually, we turned north along the fence line and then west again to check the two most distant ponds from our starting location.  We back-tracked along the same route. Nice east winds all night and all throughout the morning, with very high temps (up to high 80s F). This is a weather pattern which happens about once every fall (and normally lasts a couple days). Eventually, Josiah Clark, David Assmann, Linda Swanson, and David Tomb also arrived. Hugh, then David A both left. Tim and I left together, leaving Linda, David T and Brian still up there (from their report, they did not see many other notable birds after I left)--

trip_comments: Morning migrant flight observation and count with Vic and George with most observations from light house area and trail. This was the first impressive migrant push of the season and possibly the result of Vic returning from Sedona to give it a check. More likely it was overdue for the season, and a result of light northwest winds 5-10, and perhaps the last day of a stretch of nice weather. But, who knows. Determining the right day and conditions of major flights have been a bit of a guessing game. Regardless, we managed some impressive counts of a few species - specifically Black-headed Grosbeaks, Western Tanagers and Cedar Waxwings. Many smaller species such as Yellow Warblers were likely way under counted and not reflective of their actual numbers given many birds were a bit too high to decipher.
species_comments: Many groups with one or two large groups. Amazing that about 8-10 years ago these were a novelty here. Now, they are a expected and abundant migrant and common resident.

trip_comments: I spent about an hour wandering around the center of town along streets bounded by Third Street on the north, First Street and the community center on the south, Brookings Avenue on the west, and Fred D. Haight Drive on the east.  Concentrated time at intersection of North Street and Wallace Avenue where Orchard Orioles had been seen and where there were tow large and profusely flowering magnolia trees and what appeared to be a camellia tree.  Failed to even hear both the titmouse and the orioles, but encountered many of the same birds that had been present the previous day.  There was a 30% cover of high and very thin clouds, a mild (<5 knot to 5 knot) breeze from the east, and a temperature of 55Â° F on my arrival (based on the thermometer in the rental vehicle).  7:15-8:10 am.

trip_comments: Guy McCaskie and I, joined by John Sterling, Todd Easterla, Logan Kahle, Linda Pitman, and Dan Brown, spent about an hour walking neighborhoods in the small community of Smith River in search of an Oak Titmouse and Orchard Oriole that had been wintering here.  Our wanderings were bordered on the north by North Street and on the south by First Street (though we did check a yard on the south side of the latter just west of the Del Norte County Library.  Our western limit was along Brookings Avenue and we never made it east of the library of to Fred D. Haight Drive.  Within this small region, however, we wandered widely checking the yards, many of which had ornamental plantings, trees of various species including both conifers and deciduous trees, and also a number of hedges, flowering plants, and brambles.  Despite the rainy conditions, we encountered quite a few birds here, though the vast majority were either robins or blackbirds, though also with quite a few collared-doves and starlings.  John eventually managed to find the titmouse, and Todd found a "Yellow-shafted" Flicker, but we never did find the oriole, which had been seen the day before.  There was a dense, low overcast, and drizzle to moderately heavy rain during our visit, but it was calm at times and we had no more than a mild (5 knot) breeze that appeared to be coming from the southwest.  Temperatures continued at a steady 58Â° F (based on the thermometer in Guy's vehicle).  12:30-1:35 pm.

locality: Smith River, Mouth of Smith River Road at US 101
trip_comments: Guy McCaskie, Jim Lomax, Larry Sansone, and I spent most of the day searching for White-winged Crossbills in the vicinity of the mouth of the Smith River, where we were joined at times by Andrew Howe, Jon Dunn, and more briefly Alan Barron, Lucas Brug, and Steve Stump.  We spent most of the morning around the Salmon Harbor Resort along both Lopez Street on the south and especially Salmon Harbor Road on the north, but also with some time scanning to the west from the south side of a property storage site where Andrew reported seeing a male crossbill, followed by a brief walk through the resort from south to north.  We then drove to Mouth of Smith River Road, and walked a loop west of US 101 from Mouth of Smith River Road over Prince Island Drive and then north along the entire length of South Indian Road to the curve at the north end and then almost back to US 101.  We then spent a bit of time checking crossbill flocks in spruce trees north of Mouth of Smith River Road between US 101 and Ocean View Drive.  After returning briefly to Salmon Harbor Road in the late afternoon to find no crossbills, we returned to the site along Mouth of Smith River Road, which likewise lacked crossbills late in the day, so I walked Ocean View Drive south to Ocean Heights Way before returning along the same route.  Our day consisted of a search for White-winged Crossbills, and directed at a male that had been reported in this area the previous day by Rob Fowler.  Given our single target, we concentrated on Sitka Spruce trees that were heavily laden with ripe cones, but given that these trees were scattered across our route, we found little to concentrate the crossbills, which moved widely over this area with only occasional pauses in the tops of generally rather large spruce trees.  Andrew Howe reported seeing a male White-winged briefly, but it vanished before others could arrive and the rest of us saw identifiably only Red Crossbills.  Other birds on this list were seen mostly incidentally, but I tried to keep at least reasonable track of each species and the respective total.  It was mostly clear to partly cloudy, with a cover that ranged from 5% early to about 30% in the mid-afternoon before clearing somewhat later in our visit.  It was also generally calm, but with a mild (<5 knot) breeze that appeared to be coming from the north.  Temperature was 37Â° F on our morning arrival and 50Â° F on our late-afternoon departure, but it was seemed warmer in the early afternoon.  Overall conditions were quite good all day, albeit with brief cloud-cover in the mid-afternoon briefly resulting in less than ideal late.  8:00 am - 4:15 pm.

trip_comments: Brian Daniels, Lynda Elkin, Tristan McKee, and I spent most of the day moving back-and-forth across the Ferndale Bottoms, with much of this time spent either along Centerville Road or Russ Lane and the Eel River Estuary Preserve in search of the Gyrfalcon that we missed the previous day (7:15-8:00 am, 9:00-11:30 am).  Between time spent looking for the falcon, we also worked along both Port Kenyon Road and Goble Lane for Black-capped Chickadee along the Salt River and a Black Vulture that had been seen over the past few days near the intersection of Goble Lane and Sage Road.  We also spent some time in the hills along Poole Road in search of Gray Jay, which we are pretty sure we heard, yet we never managed to see.  The majority of our time was spent either on the reserve or Centerville Road, but with reasonable periods of time spent along Poole Road, Port Kenyon Road, and Goble Lane in decreasing order of effort.  There was a full, low overcast for much of the morning, but this cleared to partly cloudy skies by late morning.  There was a mild (5 knot) and somewhat intermittent breeze from the east for much of the morning.  Temperatures increased from 45Âº F to 54Âº F.  7:15 am - 2:15 pm.----Pacific Chorus Frog - 5 (heard-only);--Mule Deer - 8.

trip_comments: Peter Ginsburg and I were joined for part of our visit by Dave and Mary Beth Woodward at the overlook above the mouth of Alder Creek, from which we searched for the Brown Shrike that had been present here since first found on 5 March by Alison Cebula,  After finding the shrike, I walked down to the edge of the creek mouth to more carefully observe this bird as it foraged on the slope immediately north of the mouth.  I did pay moderate attention to the other birds present, yet I failed to see several of the more common species that were calling form the dense vegetation near the creek mouth.  The creek appeared to be lined with leafless willows nearly to the mouth, but there were also stands of willows on the south-facing slopes immediately north of the creek.  There were also two pastures, one small and the other quite large just east of the creek and our position, and the hillsides on our side of the creek were covered with a dense growth of coastal scrub that appeared to include Coyotebrush and a species of Ceanothus with deep blue flowers.  We arrived to an 80% cover of low clouds, yet before we even reached the creek mouth a moderately dense, yet thankfully somewhat broken, fog blew in from the west.  We therefore observed the shrike while waiting for periods of clear sky.  There was a generally mild (initially <5 knots, but later exceeding 5 knots) breeze form the northwest, and temperatures that were probably in the upper 50s.  12:45-3:30 pm.----Pacific Chorus-Frog - 1 (croaking; heard-only).

trip_comments: I spent most of the day birding with Maggie Smith in search of key birds for the upcoming Morro Bay Christmas Bird.  We spent the morning scouting the Morro Bay area, where we began by wandering around the lower parts of the golf course at Morro Bay State Park, scanning the adjacent parts of the bay, and then checking the campground (7:20-8:55 am).  Next we checked the mouth of the bay in search of a Red-necked Grebe that had been seen here intermittently, followed by a moderately thorough check of the streets of Morro Bay beginning at the west end of Olive Street but then working up the hillside towards and then around Black Hill before descending the hill along Piney Way.  Along the way we walked quickly through the neighborhoods searching out pockets of better habitat and trying our best to find something unusual.  There were relatively few birds in general, but we did find some interesting species important for the count.  Much of our time was spent wandering around the pine groves on the upper part of Black Hill.  After walking the streets, we again checked the mouth of the bay and again missed the grebe.  We were in and around Morro Bay (including the mouth of the bay) from 9:00 am to 12:45 pm.  After working Morro Bay for an extended period of time, we spent a short time at sites in Los Osos, where we began by scanning the back part of the bay from the Elfin Forest Overlook, then the Audubon Overlook, and finally Sweet Springs.  We also made a brief stop by Sea Pines Golf Course to look at some geese that were frequenting one of the "water traps."  In all, we were in Los Osos from 1:00 pm to 3:15 pm.  It was mostly clear to mostly cloudy, with a mild to moderate (generally 10-15+ knot) breeze, seemingly more from the northeast early on but more northwest later, and in the low 50s to upper 60s or possibly the low 70s.  7:15 am - 3:15 pm.----Spotted Munia 1 - (a molting juvenile at Sweet Springs);----Western Gray Squirrel - 4 (Morro Bay State Park).
species_comments: (Morro Bay)

trip_comments: Time:0800-1200--Conditions: partly overcast to clear, cool to warm, calm.--Notes: Roger and Ruth Zachary joined me to look around Morro Bay State park.  We started at the intersection of Las Tunas and La Loma where we walked into the Monterey pine forest to see if last year''s Grace''s Warbler had returned.  After seaching that are we drove to the start of the road to the maintenance area where we walked the road into the campground, and then crossed the golf course fairly to to a path of trees with flowering eucalyptus.  Then we crossed another fairway to get to Windy Cove and from there we headed back toward the campground kiosk and down the Rv road through the campground finally circling back to the cars.  Dave Lawrence showed up while we were near the maintenance area and joined ups for the rest of the walk through the golf course and back. ----The two Hermit Warblers were in the same flock on the back side of Black Hill, MBSP, in the pines near Las Tunas and La Loma where the Grace's Warbler was present last winter.  One had a very bright yellow face and veiled black throat suggesting an adult male, the other had a paler yellow face with noticeably more green on the crown and forehead, but also with what appeared to be a veiled black throat - young male/female?  The two creepers were seen together.

trip_comments: I checked my usual area for the Morro Bay Christmas Bird Count this morning.  My area represents the western part of Los Osos from the Audubon Overlook west to Shark Inlet and the Sea Pines Golf Course.  Following a quick stop at dawn to scan Sweet Springs (7:00-7:15 am), I returned to Shark Inlet and then checked the Sea Pines Golf Course.  After walking around the golf course, I worked my way through the Pecho Road willows and then along the edge of the bay to Sweet Springs.  I checked not only the main part of this reserve, but I also worked my way around the east end and then around Baywood Cove to and then around Pasadena Drive, from which I looped back east along Santa Lucia Avenue to the Audubon Overlook (AO).  Including the golf course, Shark Inlet, Sweet Springs, and the Audubon Overlook I was out from 7:35 to 11:30 am.  I then hitched a ride back to my vehicle with Maggie Smith, and after we retrieved my vehicle, Maggie showed me a new site off Los Olivos Avenue just west of South Bay Boulevard (11:35-11:55 am).  At this particular site there was a willow clump (somewhat overgrown by German Ivy) that was surrounded by an apartment house and a residential neighborhood.  We next visited the home of Mike Stiles, at 1120 13th Street, in search of Costa''s Hummingbird and (Red) Fox Sparrow (12:00-1:10 pm).  We again saw the sparrow but missed the hummingbird; I also scanned the bay off the Elfin Forest Overlook at this time.  I concluded my work in Los Osos scanning the bay from both the Audubon Overlook and the end of Pasadena Drive, primarily in search of a Long-tailed Duck that had been reported in the area over the past few days (1:15-2:00 pm).  I estimated that I walked about 7.5 kilometers and I probably drove at least this much, but I encountered few birds along the drive.  There were a few high, thin clouds, generally calm conditions apart from a mild (5-10 knot) breeze at times that switched directions, and temperatures increasing from the upper 40s to the upper 60s.  7:00 am - 2:00 pm.----Oak Titmouse - 1 (?; calling; I think I heard one but could not quite be sure);--Western Gray Squirrel - 1;--California Ground-Squirrel - 5.

trip_comments: I next spent about two hours at Oceano, where I first walked a roughly counterclockwise loop around the lagoon, and I then wandered more randomly through both the upper and lower campgrounds.  In the process, I tried to check both the willow thickets around the lagoon and the pines and eucalyptus trees in the campgrounds.  I did hear the wintering Summer Tanager and I found a Bullock''s Oriole, but most of what I encountered would have been expected given the date and locality.  I also scanned the birds at Oceano County Park, but I found nothing of note (the highlights being several Glaucous-winged Gulls and a Great-tailed Grackle), so I did not include these birds on the list below.  It was clear and initially calm, but with a mild (5-10 knot) breeze from the northeast coming up shortly after my arrival.  Temperatures seemed to increase from the upper 60s to the mid-70s, which is unusually warm for this area in mid-January.  9:40-11:40 am.

trip_comments: I spent about two hours (the latter half or so with Maggie Smith) wandering around the western part of Los Osos in search of a few birds that had been seen here over the previous weeks.  My primary targets were two Hooded Orioles (and one Bullock's Oriole) that were visiting the feeders at Jim Royer's home along Henrietta Avenue just west of Nancy Avenue, but I was also hoping to see at least one of the two Swamp Sparrows that Jim saw the previous day.  Although it took some time, we managed to see all three orioles and both Swamp Sparrows, though we each saw different sparrows.  Given that one of the Swamp Sparrows was seen in the yard at the intersection of Pecho Road and Grove Street, and the other was in the small marsh on the east side of Doris Avenue just north of Binscarth Avenue, I essentially walked a loop around the block, meeting Maggie when I returned to Jim's home.  After meeting up, we spent most of our time waiting for the orioles to appear, but we did make a second attempt to see the sparrow off Pecho Road.  I did not really check the willows on the west side of Pecho Road, but I did briefly check those at the intersection of Binscarth and Nancy Avenues.  I also saw a few waterbirds in the channel of the small marina off Doris Avenue, but I did not really look at the bay, so most of the birds were seen in the residential neighborhood.  It was mostly to partly cloudy, with a mild (<5 knot) breeze, and temperatures in the low to mid-50s.  8:40-10:40 am.
species_comments: (calling)

trip_comments: I visited Oceano twice today, both times in search of several birds that were wintering here and to see if we could find something new.  Given that our primary targets were a Summer Tanager that had been seen intermittently around the back campground and a Tropical Kingbird that had been seen more consistently on the peninsula just east of the front campground, we began along Pier Avenue and we spent most of our time west of the lagoon.  In fact, during my morning visit with Tom Edell, we worked exclusively along the east edge of the front campground, around the lagoon to the peninsula, and then through the back campground to the upper end of the lagoon before returning along roughly the same route (9:05-11:45 am).  I returned in the afternoon with Jon Dunn, when we searched roughly this same route, though this time I also walked a clockwise loop all the way around the lagoon while Jon spent most of his time along the peninsula and around the native plant garden in search of the kingbird (2:05-4:00 pm).  After checking the campground each time, we briefly scanned the gulls on and around the lagoon at the Oceano County Park (ca. 11:45-11:55 am, and again, 4:05-4:20 pm).  It was partly cloudy all day, with just a few high clouds in the morning, but more in the afternoon.  Although we had only a trace (<5 knot) breeze in the morning, there was a mild (5 knot) breeze from the northwest in the afternoon.  Temperatures seemed to increase from the mid-50s to the mid-60s in the morning, but I thought they were probably in the low to mid-60s in the afternoon.  9:05-11:55 am, and again, 2:05-4:20 pm.
species_comments: (singing)

trip_comments: Brian Daniels and I spent the better part of the morning checking the mouth of Arroyo Grande Creek, the lower kilometer of riparian corridor along the creek, and the pines that encircle the property on the south side of the creek just inside the dunes.  We began by walking out to the creek mouth from south end of Strand Way, which ended up being a more extensive search of the lagoon than we had anticipated given a good number of shorebirds and both a Ruff and a Solitary Sandpiper (7:05-8:30 am).  We were also joined briefly at this site by Maggie Smith and Tom Edell, before Brian and I moved over to check the riparian corridor.  To do so, we drove by the lagoon at the county park and around to Ocean Street and Fountain Avenue on the eastern and northern sides of the Oceano County Airport.  After a quick search of the fence lines and runways of the airport, we parked at the gate on Delta Street and walked over to work the river channel (8:40-10:05 am).  I first worked a short way upstream before entering the riverbed and walking downstream along what was initially a dry bed, but with progressively more water as I continued west until the water was too deep for my boots.  Upon exiting the riverbed, I cut over to the northern dike and then continued most of the way out to the river mouth checking both the willows and the intermittent stands of Sweet Fennel and Coyotebush.  While I did this, Brian checked the pines on the south side of the river and he walked the horse trail out to the dunes before returning and meeting me on the south side.  We found good numbers of birds, but not many obvious migrants and really nothing of note, with the highlights being a Black-chinned Hummingbird and an unseen Red-breasted Nuthatch calling from the pines.  What seemed to be a breaking, mid-level overcast with a near full cover of clouds was evident upon our arrival, yet the clouds never really cleared during our visit.  Also evident was a mild (<5 knot) breeze from the northwest and temperatures that seemed to increase from the upper 50s to the mid-60s during our visit.  7:05-10:05 am.--Although the list below does not include the lagoon at the county park, we did see about ten Great-tailed Grackles in the parking lot along Air Park Drive when we drove by on our way from the beach to the airport.----California Ground-Squirrel - 6.
species_comments: (singing; most were seen by Brian around the horse farm)

trip_comments: Kevin Zimmer and I were joined by Roger and Ruth Zachary at the edge of the bay off the north end of Pecho Road in search of an American Golden-Plover that had been found here the previous day by Jim Royer (9:30-11:20 am).  As it turned out, we easily located the plover at the edge of the marsh and we then spent an extended period of time observing and photographing this bird at close range.  We spent our time in and at the edge of the narrow strip of Salicornia bordering the flats concentrating on this one bird, but we did scan the bay, the flats and the small cove to the northeast.  We did not concentrate on the land birds in the eucalyptus trees at the end of Pecho Road or those in the adjacent yards, but we did find a few incidentally.  After our visit to Pecho Road, we spent a short time scanning from the Audubon Overlook off the end of Third Street (11:25-11:45 am), where we checked the birds along the edge of the bay, and those on both the open flats and the water.  We also encountered a few land birds incidentally.  After getting a call about Red Crossbills at Montana de Oro State Park, we cut our visit short.  A mid-level marine layer began to clear about 11:00 am.  It was calm most of the time, but a mild (5 knot) breeze from the west came up around the time the clouds began to clear.  Temperatures were probably in the upper 50s to low 60s.  9:30-11:45 am.----American Pipit - 1 (?, calling; Kevin thought he may have heard an unseen pipit as it flew over the marsh off Pecho Road).
species_comments: (most seen along the road between Pecho Road and the overlook)

trip_comments: After my visit to Morro Bay, I stopped briefly in Los Osos to look for a Black-and-white Warbler that had been reported in a yard along 3rd Street opposite Baywood Cove.  I therefore wandered along both 3rd and 4th Streets on both sides of a walking corridor that connected the two right at the yard (1502 3rd Street) where the warbler had been seen visiting trees adjacent to a backyard feeding station that attracted quite a few sparrows.  I never did find the warbler, or anything else of note, but I did see a nice selection of the expected species given the site and the date.  It was clear, calm, and with temperatures in the middle to upper 50s.  7:55-8:40 am.
species_comments: (singing)

trip_comments: I spent about two hours checking the lagoon and campgrounds at the Oceano Campground of Pismo State Beach.  I parked at the intersection of Norswing Drive and Coolidge Drive and then walked in a counterclockwise direction around the lagoon to Pier Avenue before looping back along the western edge of the lower campground, through the amphitheater area, and then back up the upper campground to the north end of the lagoon, from which I walked back down the trail to where I had parked.  The red-flowered eucalyptus trees on the peninsula were covered with flowers and many of the Blue Gum trees in the lower campground were also in bloom, but I found nothing else remarkable about the site today.  I encountered most of the expected breeding species in the park, but the only clear migrant was a singing male Western Tanager.  The loop I walked was about 2.3 kilometers in length.  I arrived to a mid-level marine-layer that cleared quickly right about 1:30 pm.  There was an intermittent, mild (5 knot) breeze that seemed to be coming from the northwest, and temperatures that I suspect increased from the low to the middle 60s during my mid-day visit.  11:50 am - 1:50 pm.----Bullfrog - 1 (an unseen frog calling from the edge of the lagoon).
species_comments: (singing)

trip_comments: I visited 7 different public parks along a 3 mile stretch of the San Luis Obispo County coastline to evaluate bird populations in areas of moderately intense public use.  I started at Dolphin Bay along Shell Beach and birded south to Dinosaur Caves Park, then north to Margo Dodd Park, Eldwayen Ocean Park, Seacliff Park, Spyglass Park, Palisdaes Bluff Walkway, and Palisades Park. I finished birding at 7:00 p.m. after an hour break for lunch.  Most of the birds on the ocean were near kelp forests just offshore with others chiefly in rocky intertidal and offshore "stacks".  There was very little in the way of sandy beach or Coastal Sage Scrub at the various parks today.  The parks were chiefly lawns with low landscaping so as not to obscure scenic coastal vistas,
species_comments: Most of these were in residential, commercial, or rural areas ... some were present in almost every park in every town I visited today,

Once there I walked along the brush to the main trail to the beach and then to the beach and up coast to Villa Creek. When I arrived there I, Kaaren Perry, Jackie Knowlton, and another man were there searching for the Lucy's Warbler found yesterday by Herb Elliott. I walked up creek along the inland side and checked the brush where Herb found it without luck. After going as far up creek as possible due to dense brush, I returned to the creek mouth and crossed the dry outlet and walked to the brush and then up the trail that led to the point and back. Once on the beach again, I walked down coast to the end of the beach and then around the rocky point there to the next cove. Halfway through that cove I headed up hill to the main bluff top trail and walked down coast about 0.42 mile (as the crow flies) scanning the ocean, rocky shoreline, beaches, and grassland/brush. I continued down coast until I reached the willow lined drainage that still held surface water. From there I walked back to the most direct trail to the parking area and then to the car. The eBird phone App calculated the total distance traveled at 3.15 miles. Using Google Earth I calculated the total one-way distance traveled at approximately 1.75 mile.

trip_comments: For the Santa Barbara Christmas Bird Count this morning I walked my usual route of about six miles around the agricultural fields, through the business park, and along Atascadero Creek (and the lowermost reaches of Maria Ygnacio Creek).  I began near the bridge over which Patterson Avenue crosses lower Atascadero Creek.  I first took a quick detour across the bike bridge to check the lowermost stretch of Maria Ygnacio Creek, after which I returned to Patterson Avenue and then walked north to Ekwill Street, which I checked east to its terminus at Maria Ygnacio Creek.  The highlight here was a row of pink-flowering eucalyptus trees on the north side of a parking lot, where I had most of my Yellow-rumped Warblers and a Selasphorus hummingbird, but nothing truly noteworthy.  I next returned to Patterson Avenue along Ekwill, and I then crossed over to and then across the southern edge of the business park on the west side of the road.  I worked north along the west side of this park, checking the large Myoporum hedge that separates the business park from the agricultural fields.  After checking the parking lots and even a yard on the north side of Hollister Avenue, I worked back south through the middle of the business park.  I next cut over to the agricultural fields, where I walked the perimeter extensively and I even checked many of the internal roads between the fields.  After walking the fields, I exited through a gate to the bike path along Atascadero Creek.  I then worked my way downstream checking the banks of the creek and the vegetation along the path.  I passed the south end of Ward Drive and checked the willow clumps on the north side of the path, but I soon returned to walk a circuit around the Rancho Goleta Mobile Home Park (mostly in search of the geese, ducks, and gulls around the lake).  Upon completing my walk around the mobile home park, I returned to Ward Drive and then the bike path, along which I worked my way back up along Atascadero Creek to Patterson Avenue and even a little beyond to recheck the lowermost 100 meters or so of Maria Ygnacio Creek.  Although it was getting late by this time, I walked out More Ranch Road to the beginning of the trail out towards Goleta Beach along the south side of the creek.  Given that Ron Hirst and Wes Fritz were working along the south side of the creek from the "gas plant" to a point opposite Goleta Beach, I checked only the beginning of this trail out to the oak trees immediately north of the plant.  On my way back, I spent a few minutes with a large goldfinch flock that was frequenting the trees near the intersection of More Ranch Road and Patterson Avenue, but by this time, I was already a little late for the mid-day meeting, so I drove straight to Goleta Beach without even stopping for lunch.  It began mostly clear, calm, and in the low 50s, but with high clouds increasing through the morning, and a mild (5-10 knot) breeze from the southwest coming up after about 9:00 am.  Temperatures seemed to increase to the upper 60s by late morning, which made conditions pleasant even if there were not many birds.  7:10 am - 12:20 pm.

trip_comments: With Chris and Jeremy for Thanksgiving at Bodega Bay.  Beautiful day with low wind, clear sky and high temp 60 degrees F.  I spent the first 3 hours (high tide) on the north end of the harbor and in the dunes campground.  The late morning was spent at the Tides Wharf observing from the restaurant.  The early afternoon was spent first at Doran Beach, mostly on the harbor side and out onto the mudflat (low tide), and mid-afternoon on Bodega Head (the walk around the south part of the headland).  Then back to Tides Wharf for early Thanksgiving dinner.  As we drove south on CA 1 at 5:20 pm (already dark), a Gray Fox ran across the road in front of us at about the turnoff to Doran Beach (into the willow thicket east of the highway).  Also saw Mule Deer on the headland and Harbor Seal and California Sea Lion in the harbor.  Three whale spouts south of Bodega Head, probably Gray Whales.

trip_comments: A dentist appointment in Simi Valley gave me yet another opportunity to look for (and miss) the wintering Worm-eating Warbler at Camino Real Park.  I spent essentially the entire morning wandering back-and-forth along the barranca in search of this bird and whatever else I could find.  I twice wandered up along the barranca to the northeast part of the park in search of the Williamson's Sapsucker, which I found on my second attempt (in the same tree where I saw it in November).  For the first time, I also walked along the southern edge of the park, where there were several dense shrubs that looked good for a Worm-eating Warbler (though with the freeway interchange on the other side of the trees it was difficult to hear much in this part of the park).  Although there was a mild breeze, the conditions seemed favorable enough that I thought I had at least a chance of finding the warbler.  There seemed to be many fewer Yellow-rumped Warblers than during my past visits to the park.  It was partly cloudy, with a cover of high, thin clouds.  A generally mild (5-10 knot) breeze was initially coming from the northeast, but it switched to the north or northwest late in my visit.  Temperatures seemed to range from the low 50s to the upper 60s (or maybe even the very low 70s) during my extended visit.  7:25-11:55 am.----Pacific Tree-Frog - 2 (calling; heard-only);--Western Fence Lizard - 2 (I glimpsed a couple of lizards that were probably this species).

trip_comments: I joined Larry Sansone for an afternoon of birding at the hunting club on the Oxnard Plain.  At the club the previous day, Larry, Jon Dunn, and others saw two Ruffs, both Stilt and Solitary Sandpipers, and a Bobolink, but we were also looking for an odd Tringa that Larry saw briefly late in the day.  Although we saw both Ruffs and both Solitary and Stilt Sandpipers, we never did find the other bird despite much time searching back-and-forth across all of the ponds that were suitable for shorebirds.  Most of the birds were either in a few ponds in the western part of the club or in one that was in the northeastern part, but there were quite a few ponds with habitat suitable for shorebirds and quite a few birds present.  We spent a short period of time checking the willow clumps and the fence line that separates the club from the naval air station, but in general, we concentrated on the shorebirds and not on land birds.  There were also not too many ducks present.  We looked briefly for a Bobolink that was seen the previous day in a pond with seeding grain located in the middle of the site, but a Peregrine that was chasing the blackbird flock pretty much eliminated our chances of seeing this bird.  The weather was quite good, with clear skies, a mild (5-10 knot) breeze, apparently from the west, and temperatures in the middle to upper 60s.  1:15-6:00 pm.----California Ground-Squirrel - 1.

Just saw a kingfisher on the bridgeâ€_-----****************************************--Thurs. July 26 to Tues. July 31, --did solo (had asked Matt if he was interested, he said to plan without him, and then he decided not to join for weekend) road birding trip to explore counties I have never been to, and get in some birding with and beachy-bird teachings from Tim Shelmerdine, thank you! : --beautiful weather all weekend, mostly sunny skies and warm/hot, some seafog esp in Florence and eventide Fort Stevens, but mostly lovely weather , and only too hot when driving highways midday; full moon was July 27, but most nights it wasnâ€™t visible.--Libby let me borrow Prius (which I slept in): --I drove from Bend west to Florence through Eugene (Fern Ridge), birded some Lane co. coast (Siuslaw River South Jetty); --then skipped Lincoln co., --drove north to Tillamook (Neskowin, Sitka Sedge, Netarts Bay, Tillamook Bay),--and Clatsop (Cannon Beach, Ecola SP, Seaside Cove, Fort Stevens SP, Brownsmead),--birded coasts, practiced beachy birds, --on Sat. Tim Shelmerdine toured me around mostly Tillamook, found me 2 Life Birds, helped teach me some beginning-ocean-birding starting tips, which I really appreciate, very helpful, I look forward to more in future! and excited about upcoming first pelagic trips;--I would have stayed overnight to bird an early morning at Fort Stevens SP , NW tip of OR, but ranger kicked me out after 10p; --then drove east to Sauvie Island, which is split Columbia and Multnomah counties : spent night in cousin Saraâ€™s hammock since not allowed to sleepover at Sauvie, so I missed out on any early morning birding, bummer ... --Overall, wonderful trip and so good for me in so many ways, grateful I did this.--(And, inland from Coast, everywhere thick with ripe enormous blackberries ! they form hedge thickets, are so large probably arenâ€™t native, are delicious.)--Having spent all my life in Oregon, I have never been on the Coast north of Lincoln Co., I have never before stepped foot in Clatsop or Columbia counties, (and only prev. a quick drive-by of Tillamook).--Really wonderful practice of birds west of Cascades, esp scoping ocean birds, and loved so so much walking beaches, I really need more of this in my life, 1-2 times a year,--I am henceforward going to incorporate regular/annual Coast trips into my life, and more exploratory road trips of Oregon outside of Central. Thanks to eBird (& Matt Cahill), am inspired now to fill out my Oregon map, all orange-colored.----Stats of this trip:----4 Life Birds: --Purple Martin--Huttonâ€™s Vireo--Tufted Puffin--Wandering Tattler----Oregon Year list jumped--from 215 to 249----Lane Co.--from 87 to 127----Tillamook Co. --from 15 to 96 ----Clatsop Co.--from 0 to 97----Columbia Co. --from 0 to ~ 72----Multnomah Co. --from 34 to 72

trip_comments: pc, 37-40F, light & variable breeze Birch Bay Marathon Course: Start/finish at Birch Bay State Park, run north 2.8 miles on Birch Bay Drive to Harborview Drive, then loop twice counterclockwise around the peninsula between Drayton Harbor and Birch Bay on Harborview, Drayton Harbor, Semiahmoo and Birch Point roads before returning south 2.8 miles back to Birch Bay State Park. This year the course included a dogleg down to the water on Semiahmoo Parkway on the first loop only. Habitat includes fresh water stream/slough, salt water shore and bay, residential areas, alder, cedar and Doug fir and mixed woods, fields and hedgerows and thickets. Tall conifers along the shore, even in residential areas, provide perches for eagles and other raptors.

trip_comments:
Absolutely amazing morning at the Holland Tract for the East Contra Costa county CBC. Sunny and clear. Temps about 40-60. Calm. With Rob Furrow, Jasen Liu, Ted Robertson, John Muir Laws, Kim Kuska, Ashok (?last name?), and myself (Logan Kahle). Rob, Jasen and I stuck together for most of the morning, joining the rest for about half the time. We all started at the Marina then Rob, Jasen and I then walked along the north side of the blackberry bramble to directly west all the way until the corner (the "channel junction" area). We then got back on the levee and walked all the way to the end of the road.----Contextual comments for Brown-crested Flycatcher (couldn't fit in the BCFL spot):--As I was looking at the White-winged Doves (see that species account for location I noticed a yellow-bellied Tyranid with gray throat and breast, brighish yellow belly, and what I thought looked like a black tail, but I realize now that that was an effect of shaddow. What I had seen had led me to believe that I'd seen a Western Kingbird (apparently put too much weight on the black tail that wasn't actually black). Three hours later and over a mile away, I said "There's the Kingbird!" before Rob Furrow and I quickly realized that it was a Myiarchus! I was utterly perplexed as to what Myiarchus to expect (no winter records of Great Crested, no Central Valley records of Dusky-capped, almost no winter Cal records of Ash-throat in winter and especially not away from the coast, and almost no pattern of vagrancy for Brown-crested). Rob then pointed out how massive the bill was and it dawned on me that this was likely a BROWN-CRESTED! I took a series of photos before the bird flew off to the north, landed, then continued north out of sight. We were never able to refind it. The total observation time through the scope was about 20ish seconds, maybe a little bit more. ----

trip_comments: 100 % low clouds. 1-3 mph wind, 65-73 *F; Tom Edell, Curtis Marantz, Maggie Smith. We parked at the north end of Creek Road (per Google Maps) and walked across the dike and into the dry Arroyo Grande Creek bed where we walked west under the willow canopy to where the pines and cypress trees started adjacent to the A-frame house on the south side of the dike. Curtis continued down creek while Maggie and I continued west along the top of the south dike.  We walked west along the dike, checked a side trail spur at the south end of the A-frame house property, and then along the sandy trail through willow riparian habitat and to the beach where we walked through the vegetated dunes to where we overlooked the southern end of the Arroyo Grande Creek mouth lagoon. The lagoon was mostly dry though there was water at the southern end and there was a small accumulation of ducks, shorebirds and gulls. Curtis rejoined us at this point and we all walked back through the dry creek mouth to the north dike and then east to a trail through the willows to Security Ave and Aloha Place. After checking the Airport and vegetation at the entrance to the wastewater plan, we walked to the end of Security Ave and through the dry lagoon to Laguna Drive, west on Utah Ave and south on Strand Way back to the south side of the creek. We then walked east along the north Arroyo Grande Creek dike back to the road crossing where we returned to the creek bed and eventually exited a little bit west of the vehicles.  We walked a short distance west along the south dike looking for a mixed flock and the returned to the cars along the south dike.  Submitted from  BirdLog NA for Android v1.9.6
species_comments: many perched on utility wires on the south side of the creek leeve

trip_comments: clear, 1-3 mph wind, 71*F; Tom Edell and Curtis Marantz. We parked along Nancy Ave and walked north to Garden Street where we checked two seed feeders and the surrounding area. Finishing there, we walked  back up Nancy and then west along Broderson to Pecho Road and up Pecho Road to the trail heading west into the willows at Henrietta Ave. We sort of randomly walked the small trails through the willows looking for birds and spent a bit of time trying to refind the Blackburian Warbler.  While looking, Jim Royer and Bill Bouton joined us in the unsuccessful search. We returned to the car along Pecho Road and Broderson Road. Submitted from  BirdLog NA for Android v1.9.6
species_comments: singing

trip_comments: 15 % cloud cover, 1-3 mph wind, 75 *F; Tom Edell and Curtis Marantz. We parked along Hwy 1 across from 5306 Hwy 1, walked through a broken down gate onto Estero Bluffs State Park. From the gate we followed a narrow path through non-native grassland to the creek mouth and then along the edge of the lagoon and to the beach where Curtis scoped the beach and ocean while I scanned with binoculars. We returned to the car along the same route and while preparing to leave spotted the White-winged dove along utility wires on the inland side of Hwy 1. We left after photographing the dove. trip_comments: Clear, 4-7 mph NE and later NW, 50*F at start; Tom Edell and Mike Stiles. We first checked a fennel row in the farm field east of the horse pastures from Silver Spur Place and then drove to and parked at the start of Creek Road (name per Google Earth). From there we walked west along Silver Spur Place to a little short of the Horse Riding Stable and then back to the car. We drove to north end of Creek Road and walked the road along the Arroyo Grande Creek berm east to check the north end of the fennel patch.  We walked the berm back to where we started and entered the riparian strip along the dry creek and walked it west to the horse trail crossing that we took back onto the south berm and then walked a short spur trail back into the willows an pines on the west side of the pond by the residence. We then walked the main trail all the way to the beach and up onto the top of the fore dune to check the small lagoon. From there we walked back to the north, crossed the dry creek bed and walked the north berm back to the horse trail, crossed the dry creek bed and walked the south berm back to the car.

trip_comments: Clear, calm, 46-72*F; Tom Edell and Herb Elliott. We parked at the north end of Creek Road and first walked south along the road and then about 0.9 mile west on Desert Ave. After returning to where we parked, we walked to the creek and then crossed through the dry creek be to the north side of the creek and walked west along the northern dike. Along the way we found a blooming wax mallow (Malvaviscus arboreus) next to a residence that was loaded with hummingbirds. We dropped into the creek bottom and continued west as we got to the west end of the trailer storage yard and walked the creek to the old road crossing that led to a gate at the private property on the south side of the creek. Gaining the top of the south dike, we walked first a short distance up creek to check the large pines and cypress, and then walked down creek to the end of these trees and took a trail that was off to the left along the west side of a mostly hidden pond on the private property. We then returned to the main trail and walked it to the dunes. At the dunes we walked up to the the top for an overlook of the north-west running Arroyo Grande Creek lagoon and the beach and ocean. When we finished checking here, we walked north along the top of the dunes to the creek and then a short distance up creek before heading southeast back to the trail on the south side of the creek. We walked back along the trail to the creek dike and then continued along it back to where we parked on Creek Road. The eBird mobile app calculated total distance traveled at 2.91 miles. I calculated the one-way distance using Google Earth at 1.4 mile.
species_comments: Singing

trip_comments: Dave Compton, Brian Daniels, and I visited the Fairview Gardens Farm in search of a Broad-tailed Hummingbird that Dave had found here the previous weekend.  My primary goal was to obtain recordings of this bird, which was fortunate given that the bird proved easier to record than to study carefully.  I spent almost my entire time here along the eastern edge of the property trying to study and record this one bird.  My search for other birds was therefore quite superficial and I missed several species seen by the others while they were looking for other birds that were seen here the previous week.  I effectively stood at the edge of the trail scanning an adjacent backyard where the hummingbird perched between visits to flowering vines in a large ash tree.  Unfortunately, the hummingbird never visited the elderberry trees on the farm property, where others had been able to study it more closely.  Given that this was an organic farm, it was both weedier and more heterogeneous than are most commercial farms, which also made it better for birds.  There were high, thin clouds, calm conditions, and temperatures in the upper 60s.  7:55-8:55 am.
species_comments: (I missed birds seen by the others)

trip_comments: I joined Louis Bevier and Paul Lehman for a morning of scouting sites in Isla Vista and Goleta for the Santa Barbara Christmas Bird Count.  We began in Isla Vista at the west end of Fortuna Road at Tierra de Fortuna Park, a traditional spot for unusual, wintering orioles, including a male Orchard Oriole that has spent the last few winters in this area.  From the park, Louis and I walked a loop first to the north by some maintenance buildings and then along the west side of the preschool to the gardens on the north side of Slough Road.  After looping our way through the gardens, we checked the eucalyptus trees immediately to the east.  We then walked along the slough to look for an Olive-sided Flycatcher that had been seen near the intersection of Slough Road and an unmarked road that cut over to West Campus Lane, from which we eventually worked our way back to where we parked at the end of Fortuna Road.  While we did this, Paul worked to the south along the eucalyptus row that separates Isla Vista from the university property to the west, but I am not sure what other sites he visited.  It was clear, with a trace breeze from the northeast, and temperatures that increased from the upper 30s to the low 50s during our morning walk.  7:20-9:25 am.
species_comments: (singing and calling)

trip_comments: Joan Lentz, with help from Mark Holmgren as assistant leader, took the bird class to Refugio State Beach looking for migrants.  We were slammed with a Sundowner wind -- warm -- with gusts to 20 mph.  Birding conditions were absolutely miserable, with blowing dust and little bird activity!  However, we managed to pull out a few species,  but I have to say it was not pleasant!  As usual the class was up for it.  Participant Glenn Kincaid had seen a Tropical Kingbird about an hour before, but he said the wind was howling very early on.  By the time we left the area (see checklist for " Refugio first creek crossing", the winds had calmed somewhat.
species_comments: Aside from the gulls, this was the most common species visible in the campground area.
